In article <gradyCt1FFG.BKn@netcom.com>, grady@netcom.com (Grady Ward) writes:
> 
> The problem I have is not the distinction between patents and trademarks or
> copyrights.  The problem I have is the apparent attitude of a person who
> believes that a bank accumulating money is wrong (so he relieves them of
> it without benefit of legal process) and then turns around and complains
> when someone tresspasses on his property.

If A is a subset of B, and C is a subset of B, does that mean A == C ?

This is one of the oldest and most dangerous kinds of deception.
Take something you don't like, and apply a label to it that lumps
it in with things that other people don't like, and claim
that the first thing is the same as all of the others.

Those who want other examples need only remember the Persian Gulf Massacre.

